Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Shute","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon): habitational name from any of several places called with Middle English <i>shute</i>, Old English <i>scīete</i> ‘projecting piece of land’ (often in the corner of a parish), in particular those in Devon, which include Shute near Axminster, Shute in Kelly, Shute in Ugborough, Shute in Shobrooke, Shute Farm in Bishopsteignton, and Shewte in Bovey Tracy. Other sources of the surname may include Shute Farm in Longbridge Deverill and Shute Farm in Donhead Saint Mary (both Wiltshire).","In some cases also an Americanized form of Croatian and Slovenian <b>Šute</b>, and probably also of its cognate <b>Šutej</b> (see   Shutey  ). Compare   Shutte   and   Schutte  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Shutes","meanings":["English: variant of   Shute  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Shutt","meanings":["English: variant of   Shute  .","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>schut(te)</i>, <i>schit(te)</i> ‘archer’ (Old English <i>scytta</i>, a derivative of <i>scēotan</i> ‘to shoot’). Compare   Shutter  .","Americanized form of German   Schutt   or   Schott  ."]},{"name":"Shutey","meanings":["(2010: NA)","Americanized form of Croatian and Slovenian <b>Šutej</b>: nickname derived from Croatian (and possibly also Slovenian dialect) <i>šut</i> ‘without horns/ears’, also ‘mutilated, lame’, or perhaps from a derivative of Croatian <i>šutjeti</i> ‘to be silent’, Slovenian dialect <i>šut(l)ati</i> ‘to work silently’. Compare   Shute   and   Schutte  ."]}]},{"name":"Avis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French form of the ancient Germanic name <i>Aveza</i>, derived from a short form of one or more compound names containing the first element <i>av</i> (as in   Ava ;  the meaning is uncertain). The correspondence in form to the Latin word <i>avis</i> ‘bird’ is coincidental."],"variants":[{"name":"Avice","meanings":["From a Norman French form of the ancient Germanic name <i>Aveza</i>, derived from a short form of one or more compound names containing the first element <i>av</i> (as in   Ava ;  the meaning is uncertain). The correspondence in form to the Latin word <i>avis</i> ‘bird’ is coincidental."]}]},{"name":"Hawise","type":"FIRST","meanings":["This female name (which has been corrupted down to Avice and Avis) is from Hadewisa, formed from the German name Hedvig, same as Edwig, which Wachter translates 'propugnator felicitatis;' say, 'fortunate soldier.'"],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":11,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":42,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lif